Text.Value: Alone, Orpheus will be much easier to control.
A fine idea. Or at least, an idea.
The moment I found it, I felt a change. My free will returning. I followed the feeling inside -
You continue to surprise me.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The Emperor reacts with surprise.

Text.Value: You absolute horror!
Take care. Illithids evolve nothing - they only enslave.
She kept him this way because she was reluctant to eradicate such power, power that she might one day wish to take from him.
Why did you deceive me all this time?
If the rest of your people ever find out what she has done, there will be civil war. Your 'queen' will be finished.
If the githyanki ever find out what she has done, there will be civil war. Vlaakith will be finished.
Are you sure of this course? It is not one that can be reversed, I fear.
I am relieved you have embraced your potential enough that you could help me eliminate them.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: He leaves Orpheus' side. We focus on Emperor and us now.

Text.Value: Gortash sent me on a mission to retrieve the Astral Prism. I was one of many, but the first to find it.
On reflection, I've changed my mind. Please don't evolve me.
Your mind is - truly - something special.
There may come a time when that is necessary, but there is no guarantee that his power would survive his passing. The risk is too great.
Lord Gortash was one of the Chosen in the colony...
I was someone once. Someone just like you.
Not all mind flayers are alike.
*A wave of disappointment, stronger than any you've ever felt, and then - stillness. You have resisted your illithid instincts. For now.*
Well aren't you clever?
Why do you say that?
Perhaps you will change your mind again when you see more of what our enemy can do.
I shall look forward to sharing his downfall with you.
It is the same power that enabled his mother Gith to bring about the fall of the Illithid Empire aeons ago, a power she passed on to him, and that I leveraged for you.
It is the same power that enabled Orpheus' mother to bring about the fall of the Illithid Empire aeons ago, a power she passed on to him, and that I leveraged for you.
Thank you. That was too close.
It wants to evolve, but it cannot do so alone. It must commune with another.
Some of your people still revere him, in defiance of their teachings. Vlaakith was safe as long as you believed him dead. But as you can see, he is very much alive.
Some githyanki still revere him, in defiance of their teachings. Vlaakith was safe as long as they believed him to be dead. But as you can see, he is very much alive.
I owe everything to that? Oh I don't like this one bit.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly repulsed, just found out his ally is a mindflayer

Text.Value: So - do you wish to evolve or not?
Any advantage I could gain by restoring my original appearance, I already had to hand in the form of magic, and that humanoid shape you've come to know.
I sustained myself on criminals. Unglamorous, but there were plenty of them, rarely missed, and they fuelled me while I did my work.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: A prison. Shadows flit over the prison’s walls by candlelight. A scream. Shot of mind flayer, wearing the garments we later find in the Elfsong Tavern (garments that disguise its true form) suckling on a criminal’s brain in its cell. The door has been broken open by its psionic strength.

Text.Value: Don't do it! This isn't evolution, it's... it's... I don't know what it is.
I'm no illithid, and never will be.
Were you imprisoned here too?
*Even though he is subdued, you feel Orpheus' revulsion - a pulsing hatred that cannot be contained. The Emperor is telling the truth. To him, you are just another wretched illithid.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Show Orpheus glaring at you

Text.Value: Tsk'va! Whatever this ghaik offers is no gift to you.
*Orpheus - Gith's son, the so-called 'traitor prince', slain by Kith'rak Voss himself millennia ago. Or so you believed.*
I changed my mind. I don't want to do that right now.
Vlaakith wanted his power. He refused. And so she sealed him within this Prism. His honour guard, ever loyal, followed him in.

I had the good fortune to meet Duke Stelmane. We formed a partnership, and through her I became the governing force behind the Knights of the Shield, the largest mercantile operation in Baldur's Gate.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor and Stelmane looking over a big map on a table
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Emperor in Stelmane’s office, colluding with her over a big map of the city on the table. While we look at the map, the ‘reach’ of the Knights of the shield is visualised across the map as more and more regions come under their control.

Text.Value: I understand. Let us hope, then, that your present self will be sufficient to deal with three gods of death and a giant, magically enhanced elder brain.

EditorData.NodeContext: with a touch of sarcasm - these are BIG almost impossible-to-defeat things

Text.Value: No, I won't do it.
You are already more illithid than you realise - it has improved you.
He tore me from my home and brought me back to the brain where I became a slave once again. A slave he continued to call the Emperor.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor thrown to the ground, looks up and stare at the elder brain
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot from Emperor’s POV of chains and magic lashing, binding him. Blurring in and out as if fading in and out of consciousness. Next conscious moment: staring at the stars through bars on the back of some sort of horsecart. Next conscious moment: the mind flayer colony coming into view. Mind flayers turn to stare. Next conscious moment: the elder brain, and beside it, Gortash.

Text.Value: We're alike in other ways too.
A history writ by whose hand?
While my body was within the Prism's bounds, my mind was free. I could resist the elder brain, the Chosen. Better yet, I could plan to overthrow them.
Well chosen. An accursed advantage - but an advantage all the same.
That would be a terrible idea.
Do you know how hard it was to find that? To cultivate it to be safe for communion?
I don't like what you're implying...
*The tadpole prickles with excitement, its thoughts rampant and chaotic in its rush to communicate with you. It is impossible to discern any single intention.*
If you let me, I can evolve you.
Thank you for saving me.
An adventurer. I came from Baldur's Gate, though I was never one to be constrained by circumstance. I longed for more.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Adventurer jumps over the wall with feather falls
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: We see the adventurer, hooded, his identity unknown, sitting atop one of Baldur’s Gate’s outer walls. One one side, the city. On the other, the wilderness. A glance to the wilderness, and we see him drop off to that side of the wall.

Text.Value: I am a mind flayer, yes. Without me you would be a slave to the Absolute.
Would you like to do it? Would you like to evolve?
Your reluctance to help nearly cost us everything. You saw reason just in time.
And found Orpheus.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot of Orpheus

Text.Value: I guess this is our best chance. You can handle it. And I'll still like you just the same.
Now hold out your hand.
*Your thoughts turn to the caged githyanki. Is this the target Vlaakith asked you to slay?*
Actually, I'd rather not.
For years I served the elder brain - the one you know as the Absolute. I was a thrall like any other. But I was fortunate. I broke free, and started a new life in my old city.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot of elder brain, psionic charges emanating off it, connecting to legions of mind flayers. We see our mind flayer walking at night, cloaked, down a street in the city. It looks around to make sure it wasn’t followed, before disappearing through a door.

Text.Value: His power has been the source of your continued protection against the voice of the Absolute - the power to disrupt hivemind communication.
If I'd known you would be so open-minded, I could have saved myself a lot of effort.
Well... certainly brave of you, I'll say that much.
That longing brought me to Moonrise Towers on a search for treasure. To a colony of mind flayers who caught me, changed me into what I am now.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Adventurer walks up to Moonrise with a map, headache, and in next cut he's strapped ot a chair, and a mindflayer approaches and puts a tadpole in his eye
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
A boot stomps on a jutting piece of land (like the final step to get to the top of Everest.) The other boot follows. The adventurer has stopped there. A map in his hand. He's arrived: Moonrise Towers (before the shadow-curse.)

Cut to: mind flayer approaching the back of a board on which the adventurer is strapped and struggling. The mind flayer carries a tadpole (throwback to intro cinematic.) Closeup of the adventurer's eye as the tadpole goes in. Fade to black to screams of the adventurer. Fade in: Shot of the same room, clasps being undone on the board. A naked mind flayer rises - the Emperor.

Text.Value: Most certainly Orpheus. He is a threat to her reign.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor hovers preparing spell, Orpheus chained staring
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The Emperor hovers down to where Orpheus is chained. He brings psionic energy to his hands. Closeup of Orpheus’ face, eyes looking at Emperor with fear and hatred. Sweat dripping.

Text.Value: Drop it on the ground and stomp on it.
Open your mind to the tadpole.
The return of Gith's son would mean the end of Vlaakith. There is no plainer truth.
You or your allies - it has vitality enough for you all.
As an illithid, I have far surpassed who I ever was before. You, too, should embrace this change.
That's a bell you can't unring. Perhaps you should reconsider.
It's like I said before - I'm just like you.
I realised that returning to my former self would only impose limitations.
I didn't realise mind flayers could be independent thinkers.
On the contrary, Vlaakith is quite fallible. Not all githyanki eyes are so clouded as yours.
I'm pleased to hear that. You will do very well as an illithid.
The return of Gith's son would mean the end of Vlaakith. There is no plainer truth.
Like it or not, our chances of defeating the elder brain are substantially improved if you embrace your latent illithid potential.
We may look different, but to the elder brain we are already the same - thralls in its design.
*If you let it, it will evolve you, just as the Emperor said.*
I suppose if it works...
How did you end up in here?
*The tadpole screams for growth with painful intensity. It has been starved - of life, of purpose. It welcomes your probing like a void waiting to be filled.*
The transformation will not be complete - the physical alteration in particular will be only partial. But your potential will certainly be amplified.
By Balduran's helm, only a fiend or fool would bargain with this damnable creature.
You are not ready yet. Keep hold of it then, until you are.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: With a quick hand gesture, the Emperor psionically closes our fingers around the astral-touched tadpole.

Text.Value: You have seen what I can do. Imagine yourself with the same strength. The same intelligence. The same devastating beauty.
Why did Orpheus refuse to aid Vlaakith?
Why did Orpheus refuse to aid Queen Vlaakith?

EditorData.logicalname: Didn't receive Vlaakith mission in Creche

Text.Value: The moment he is free, he will attack you. Your only defence would be to kill him. And in so doing, you would doom us both.
You heard the Chosen - the brain has gone to the city, and the army marches to follow.
*The tadpole's essence courses through you - where it touches, your flesh, glands, organs contract and flood with pure thought.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player transforms into a partial-illithid. Veins light up under the skin as the transformation makes its way around their body. They observe their own body parts as it works its way around.

Text.Value: I'm happy to have more powerful friends, but... well, better you than me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player wants to transform into a half-mind flayer

Text.Value: *You feel... different. Your body has never felt more connected. Your mind present in every flex of a joint or muscle.*

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Player looking at the changes to their body
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The transformation is over. The player opens their eyes and takes in the change in their skin with surprise, but not displeasure.

Text.Value: But in case you change your mind -
I have always valued freedom above all else. In my past life and present.
I would like that.
It was necessary. Rare are those that would openly consider a partnership with a mind flayer.
I'm trying to avoid becoming a mind flayer - I thought you agreed to protect me.
When your allies see what you can do... I hope you'll encourage them to try it for themselves.
There will be... physical alterations, of course. But only partial. You will retain most of your current form.
Go ahead - I cannot leave with you, but I will continue to protect the infected.
Your trust in Vlaakith is understandable. Her lie is carved in your people's slates, bold as truth - yet a lie it remains.
A very good question. One that I have been unable to answer.
Since you destroyed my gift, there is nothing further I can do for you right now. Proceed.
Two - why would I? You have done well with the limited form you have, but you would do far better as an illithid.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Emperor gestures at the player vaguely.

Text.Value: *To owe your life to a deceitful illithid - you could never have imagined a truth so obscene.*
The more I talk to you, the less you seem like a mind flayer.
The name was intended as a slight - to remind me of the heights from which I fell. But I have grown fond of it. It encapsulates well who I've become.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor being mindmelded, floats up to join the colony of mindflayers hovering around elder brain
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot that pans out from the Emperor, showing it to be one among many (though wearing its distinctive garb). Non-mindmeld Emperor’s hand waves, wiping away the image, revealing it standing there before us. Mindmeld over.

Text.Value: When Orpheus' mother left, a usurper took her place - Vlaakith declared herself 'queen' of your people.
When Orpheus' mother left, a usurper took her place - Vlaakith declared herself 'queen' of the githyanki.
No more lies, no more tricks. I will have answers!
But we mustn't lose focus. We need to resume our journey.
Even if my original body remained intact after I transformed, I would not return to it. Doing so would only impose limitations.
Prince Orpheus, son of the first leader of the githyanki.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Focus on Orpheus. Emperor begins to walk and talk around Orpheus.

Text.Value: Vlaakith is eternal. My people would not be swayed by this false prince.
But I'm glad you're not here to judge.
Even as you are, you have shown rationality that puts you far above your kind. You will do well as an illithid.
If you can evolve me, why can't you stop ceremorphosis altogether?
Was it you or Orpheus that Queen Vlaakith wanted us to kill when she ordered us inside the Prism?
Was it you or Orpheus that Vlaakith wanted us to kill when she ordered us inside the Prism?
Control him? Bah - the traitor must be ripped apart, brain to belly!
We must not let them reach it. We must find the brain, and bring it under our control.
But if you had opened your mind to it rather than consuming it, your allies could have taken advantage of its power as well.
Indeed. His hubris knows no bounds. To enslave me, that was his nature. But to enslave an elder brain? A questionable decision.
I realised what the Prism was for - containment.
Bound by infernal chains, Orpheus could never leave. Bound by duty, his guard never would.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Focus on infernal chains.

Text.Value: The moment his protection is gone, you would become enthralled to the elder brain just as I would.
*A raging pain tears through your head as thoughts and instincts do battle within it. Then - silence. Your mind opens, and all resistance evaporates...*
You grew attached to a mere disguise. But you judge without even knowing me.
All I needed to do was subdue Orpheus and find allies in the outer world. You.
Perhaps you will be more inclined to try it when you see more of what our enemy can do.

You seek to reverse an inevitable process, a process of evolution. When I first escaped from the elder brain, I too railed against the change. But the longer I have inhabited this form, the more it has grown on me.
Your histories are fabrications. The prince was not killed, as you can very well see - he was imprisoned.
I suppose it was considerate of you not to bring it up before. And I ask that you do not judge me for it now.
That githyanki in the sphere - who is it?
No. No way.
But it was important enough to them that Gortash sent me to retrieve it.
*Even as you say the words, you feel a lurch of disappointment. Your mind bristles with illithid potential. How could you be so cruel as to deny yourself what you want most in the world?*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Emperor pulls us into a mindmeld.

Text.Value: Did you have to eat criminals' brains?
How Gortash or the other Chosen learned of its existence, I do not know.
I'm glad you think so. I agree. But there is one thing you have that I do not.
A mind flayer? How is this possible? Gods, we've been so... blind.
They were close to breaking my hold on their prince - and if they had succeeded, we would be lost.
You have already benefited from that tadpole of yours.
I always suspected you were a mind flayer.
Rather them than potential future allies... like you.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor reinforce barrier, Orpheus head roll up and eyes roll to white
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
The Emperor raises his arms. A beam of light goes out, reforming the globe of domination around Orpheus. Orpheus’ head rolls back, his eyes roll back to the whites again. All is still once more. 

The Emperor turns and approaches the player.

Text.Value: Don't look at me like that.
Look after it. Use it when you are ready to evolve.
Do as it says.
Probe at the tadpole's intentions.
But you are not the one I wish to speak with. Bring me your leader.
It has been a burning need within me for as long as I can remember.
Do it. I'd like to evolve.
There is nothing further I can do for you right now. Consider using my gift.
Consider using the tadpole. Your evolution will be a benefit to us both.
How did Gortash and the other Chosen find out about the Astral Prism?
I ask again - who are you? And I'm going to need a name this time.

EditorData.logicalname: Asked Who Mind Flayer is Before

Text.Value: I do not have the privilege of knowing the answer, but the consequences are clear enough.
Was it something I said? Never mind.
I felt that. It's your nature. You cannot fight it, so - embrace it.

EditorData.NodeContext: with pleasure - he felt that you are at war with yourself and now open to doing the thing he wants

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player holds out their hand. The Emperor takes out an astral-touched tadpole and psionically manoevures it into the player's open palm. It looks like an inert rock.

Text.Value: You were in the Prism all this time? Why did you deceive me?
My original body was destroyed when I transformed. Yours continues to limit you.
You are not the leader. I will speak with your leader.
Bring me your leader.
I will only speak with the one in charge.
Vlaakith wanted his power, but Orpheus rose against her. And so she sealed him and his honour guard within this Prism.
The answer is twofold. One - I can, but it would kill you. As I told you before.
I appreciate that. But this is what I am.
We fought to tame Prince Orpheus, the son of Gith herself.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Focus on Orpheus. Emperor begins to walk and talk around Orpheus.

Text.Value: That Gortash and the Chosen found out about it... this is impossible to explain.
On the contrary, Vlaakith is quite fallible. Not all githyanki eyes are so clouded as yours.
You may call me the Emperor.
Control him? Tsk'va - you must return him to his people!
A mind flayer? Not the saviour I'd been hoping for.
Since you ingested my gift instead of using it, there is nothing further I can do for you right now. Proceed.
We have had our disagreements - but in the end you always do what needs to be done.
It's obscene - to owe my life to a damned ghaik.
Eat it.
Waste. Utter waste.
Quite possible, I assure you.
No.
Denial will change nothing.
Orpheus? Impossible. He was slain by Jhe'stil Kith'rak himself!
*A coldness seeps through your veins as the tadpole awakens, its yearning almost unbearable. Your mind is a veritable feast.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot of the inert stone that contains the astral-touched tadpole glowing with life at its core.

Text.Value: You carry a tadpole. As far as Orpheus is concerned, you are already illithid - a sworn enemy. Just like me.
My needs were sated. I was... happy. For a while. Until my true nature was discovered by the tyrant himself - Lord Gortash.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Stelmane and Emperor sitting and toasting to each other, door burst open, turns to door, Gortash appears
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Emperor and Stelmane toasting to their success in her office. (Emperor’s drink should probably look like brain parts rather than humanoid alcohol.) A bang as the door bursts open. They both look at the door in horror.

Text.Value: What are you -

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Player tilt up head and swallow stone
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player tilts their head back and drops the stone in. The Emperor looks disconcerted by this.

Text.Value: I believe we'll have a better chance of defeating the elder brain if you embrace your latent illithid potential.
What is it?
What would that entail?
And you will soon see that the benefits outweigh any perceived loss.
All I needed to do was subdue the githyanki and find allies in the outer world. You.
Feels wonderful, doesn't it? You wear it well.
Go to the city. Try out your new form. Enjoy it.
Understandable. It's a big decision. Keep it until you're ready.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Emperor psionically close player hand on the stone
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: With a quick hand gesture, the Emperor psionically closes our fingers around the astral-touched tadpole.

Text.Value: An unnerving revelation. But if this is our protector, so be it.
A ghaik illusion, an abomination - as I've suspected.
Perhaps you will be more inclined to try it when you see more of what our enemy can do.
*Your nature is no longer your own - you are well on your way to fulfilling your illithid potential. You are ready to evolve.*
It has enough vitality to further your evolution and your allies'.
What happens if we free Orpheus?

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Player throw stone to ground and stomp to pieces
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player drops the astral-touched tadpole on the ground and stomps it into pieces.

Text.Value: Even those who are on a path of becoming one.
Tell me everything.
Of all the beings to be indebted to... a bloody mind flayer.
To owe one's life to a mind flayer? It seems to make mockery of this entire struggle.
I don't understand. The histories claim the prince was burned to ash in the skies.
A little more caution would be wise. Such power is tempting, but you risk losing yourself.
I prefer the other version of you.
Yes.
Could we kill Orpheus and seize his power?
My original body was destroyed when I transformed.
When I first escaped from the elder brain, I searched for a new vessel. But the longer I inhabited this one, the more it grew on me.
I've been studying you for a while now. I believe I can trigger the next stage of your tadpole's lifecycle while continuing to preserve your independence.
You are... exquisite.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The Emperor looks you up and down. A shot of the player in partial-illithid form.
EditorData.InternalNodeContext: He's admiring you, perhaps even a little turned on. In a hungry kind of way.

Text.Value: You will be able to do things you never thought were possible.
Vlaakith is eternal! My people would not be swayed by this... this false prince.
And found the githyanki.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot of Orpheus

Text.Value: Ghaik lies, the whole lot. Orpheus is dead. The history is written!
Why did Orpheus refuse to aid Vlaakith?
Why did Orpheus refuse to aid Queen Vlaakith?

EditorData.logicalname: Didn't receive Vlaakith mission in Creche

Text.Value: I am a mind flayer, yes. And the one who saved you. Again.
Don't look at me like that.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shot of player's uneasy reaction to the Emperor being a mind flayer.

Text.Value: That Orpheus lives at all is ruinous to Vlaakith - she has done everything in her power to keep his existence a secret.
You and your allies - it has enough vitality to nourish you all - to further your evolution.
So are you going to tell me what this battle was about?
And so we should swoon and offer a kiss, abomination? I would not even know where to plant it.
By the living gods - no more visions, no more lies. I expect answers. Now.
People referred to me as the Emperor - such was my influence. Though, of course, they had no idea what I really was.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [LILI] Continue from looking at map, Stelmane and Emperor turns to look at the merchant
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Stelmane conducting business with a merchant. The merchant eyes the door to her office warily. Through a gap in the door, we see the vague outline of the Emperor like an unidentified mob boss sitting in its chair. Eyes faintly glowing, shape indiscernible. We see the merchant's unease.

Text.Value: A tadpole, nurtured by the psionic energy of the Astral Plane. Cocooned here for millennia, it has become extraordinary.
*You may resist now, but it's too late. You already embraced the powers the parasite gave you. You leveraged them to manipulate, to dominate, to survive.*
I'm nothing like you.

Synopsis: With Orpheus subdued, players learn of the true nature of Daisy, some of the Emperor's backstory, the technicality of how Orpheus' power protects them, and the scale of what they are up against when it comes to the Brain's intelligence. They might transform into a half-illithid.
